objects.name: Automated access control policy assignment or attribute-based assignment
objects.description: An assignment of access control policies based on attribtues utilizes the attributes of identities and access control policies for assignments. This thus creates a more dynamic and automated assignment of access control policies.

objects.name: Automation of account cleansing
objects.description: Especially orphan or outdated accounts might still be able to access sensible information or functions. Deprovision of these thus effectively terminates excessive access within the managed systems.

objects.name: Definition of sufficient mover processes
objects.description: Mover processes should manage granting required and revoking obsolete access when an identity is moving towards a new position. Revoking obsolete access thus can help to mitigate excessive access.

objects.name: Regular recertifications of accounts
objects.description: Responsible identities for IAM entities (like roles, permissions, accounts and identities), should periodically check their entities. This mitigates risks of outdated entities or their assignments. E.g. idenities with excessive access should at least be noticed during recertifications.

objects.name: Excessive access
objects.description: Identities may keep critical access control policies which can be used for potential attacks. Especially having administrative access control policies, this can quickly lead to a privilege escalation attack.

objects.name: Processes for attribute changes
objects.description: Suitable processes for attribute changes can maintain the attribute quality for IAM entities. E.g. these processes might enforce restrictions like nullable attributes, regular expressions, or default values.

objects.name: Validity checks for attributes quality policies
objects.description: Automated checks for validity of attribute quality rules and clearance process.

objects.name: Low data quality
objects.description: Data quality errors may enable attackers to get access to critical objects (e.g., critical permission is not flagged as critical --> no additional approvals needed).

objects.name: Automated account cleansing
objects.description: Automated provisioning technologies and processes can automatically detect and delete orphan accounts.

objects.name: Definition of a suffiecient idenity lifecycle
objects.description: Especially leaving identities need special consideration: Their accounts need to be terminated to render unusable.

objects.name: Regular account recertifications
objects.description: Recertifications are a manual and periodical check of the present accounts. Responsible identities, like managers in an enterprise context, can determine wheter an account is orphan.

objects.name: Orphan accounts
objects.description: Accounts may remain usable and have assigned access rights. Especially having administrative access, this can quickly lead to a privilege escalation attack.

objects.name: Processes for attribute changes
objects.description: Suitable processes for attribute changes can maintain the attribute quality for IAM entities. E.g. these processes might enforce restrictions like nullable attributes, regular expressions, or default values.

objects.name: Validity checks for attributes quality policies
objects.description: Automated checks for validity of attribute quality rules and clearance process.

objects.name: Error-prone assignment rules
objects.description: On assignment rule errors, some identities might receive too many access control policies while others might receive too less. Excessive access imposes a violation of the principle of least priviledge (confidentiality, integrity) and missing access hampers smooth operations of an organization (availability).

objects.name: Anonymization of privacy-related information
objects.description: Privacy-related information are effectively protected by anonymization techniques (e.g. macro data or perturbative or non-perturbative anonymizaiton of micro data).

objects.name: Encryption of privacy-related information
objects.description: Privacy-related information can be protected by encryption. This approach is especially important for use cases where the private data needs to be retrieved later from an authorized identity.

objects.name: Regualar recertifications
objects.description: Due to regular recertifications, excessive access to privacy-related information of an identity can be identified.

objects.name: Privacy Leak
objects.description: Privacy-related information can be used by attackers for further attacks (e.g., Spear Phishing Attacks). Leakage of privacy-related information may result in financial or image loss (e.g., GDPR penalties).

objects.name: Automation of processes
objects.description: Automated processes tend to be less error-prone. E.g. a self-service process can streamline authorization requests which eases and accelerate their processing.

objects.name: Process integration
objects.description: Processes can be integrated in centralized IAM workflows. This gives vision and more consistency for IAM processes. Process Errors can be identified quicker and more precise.

objects.name: Process bypass
objects.description: Attackers may want to bypass defined processes in order to gain elevated access without a mandatory approval.

objects.name: Delete dead access control policies
objects.description: Establish a structured process to technically delete dead access control policies.

objects.name: Assign owners for access control policies
objects.description: Definition of sufficient owner structure to identify dead access control policies.

objects.name: Get vision for access control policies
objects.description: Apply automated checks for dead access control policies for reporting.

objects.name: Dead access control policies
objects.description: Access control policies, which are still in existence can be used by an attacker to gain privileged access rights. As long as entitlements are not technically deleted they can still be used at any time.

objects.name: Automatically check access control policies for liveness
objects.description: Automated checks for the liveness of access control policies establish a vision for specialsts which hamper smooth operations on move or leave.

objects.name: Redesign assignments for access control policies
objects.description: The access control policy might need more assignments to identities. E.g. a realization of access control policies as roles add specialist access control polcies to a broader spectrum of identities.

objects.name: Access control policy liveness (specialist entitlement)
objects.description: Access control policies are only assigned to one identity in the entire domain. After leave or move of specialist identity the access control policy can not be used anymore (until it is manually assigned to further identities).

objects.name: Automated recertification processes
objects.description: Recertification processes need tool-based support. These tools automate the assignment of recertification tasks and allow for delegation.

objects.name: Reporting of not recertified entities
objects.description: Tool-support can establish a reporting for non-recertified entities. This gives vision about problematic or outdated entities of an organization.

objects.name: Outdated entities due to missing recertification
objects.description: Entities without recertification may grant access to undesired objects. Attackers might gain elevated access.

objects.sod_rule: Quality needs to be assured externally

objects.name: Automated SoD checks
objects.description: An automated check (e.g. on every new access control policy assignment or on a nightly basis) provides vision for SoD violation. Effective measures are prevent or revoke the assignment

objects.name: (Re-)design of SoD policies
objects.description: Issues with SoD violations might indicate a problem with their design. Frequent violations thus might be redesigned (e.g. a basic role might not need a toxic access control policy). Additionally, an access control policy might be falsely flagged as toxic, making a reevaluation relevant.

objects.name: Toxic combination of authorizations
objects.description: Identities may have toxic permission combinations assigned. Using a combination of two or more permissions can lead to potentially dangerous actions (e.g., creation and approval of invoice). SoD violations can lead to unwanted outflow of information or access to resources.
